The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Uco net dips on lower treasury profit

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Uco Bank chairman V. Sridar in Calcutta on Thursday. Picture by Kishor Roy Chowdhury

 Calcutta, May 5: Uco Banks net profit has dipped 20.46 per cent to Rs 346 crore in 2004-05 compared with Rs 435 crore in the previous financial year. The drop is mainly on two accounts ? lower treasury profit, down at Rs 192 crore from Rs 351 crore, and higher provisioning.

 The bank has made higher provisioning of Rs 473 crore in 2004-05 compared with Rs 364 crore in the previous year.

 Operating profit has increased 2.5 per cent to Rs 819 crore from Rs 799 crore in the previous year.

 The bank did business worth Rs 77,704 crore till March 31, 2005, with a growth rate of 28.25 per cent against Rs 60,587 crore in the previous year.

 Total deposits of the bank reached Rs 49,470 crore with total advances at Rs 28,234 crore. The improvement in deposits and advances led to an increase in market share ? which is 2.48 per cent in terms of deposits against 2.23 per cent in March 2004 and 2.34 per cent in respect of advances against 2.29 per cent as of March 2004.

 ?This fiscal, the bank plans to do business worth Rs 1 lakh crore, which will be combination of deposits of Rs 61,500 crore and advances of Rs 38,500 crore,? chairman and managing director V. Sridar said.

 The bank has made a recovery of Rs 678 crore in 2004-05, which includes a cash of Rs 344 crore. The bank aims to bring down the net NPA level to 1.5 per cent of the advances.

 Uco bank will open 50 branches this year. It has already received the RBIs approval for opening a representative office in Malaysia. The bank will also enter China, Thailand, Sri Lanka and Bangladesh.

 Capital rejig 

 Uco Bank is conducting a capital restructuring exercise in consultation with the Union finance ministry to increase its return on asset.

 Sridar said the capital base of the bank is Rs 800 crore. ?This is affecting the return on asset. If we restructure our capital then the shareholders will gain.? 




